issue.title: Analysis: CPU usage in pod test-app:8001
issue.body:
# CPU Usage Analysis

## Pod Information
- **Pod Name**: test-app:8001
- **Namespace**: default

## Analysis
The logs show normal application behavior but the pod is experiencing high CPU usage leading to restarts. The root cause appears to be in the cpu_intensive_task() function which runs an unoptimized brute force path finding algorithm with a large graph size (20 nodes) and no rate limiting or timeout controls. This creates excessive CPU load through aggressive thread usage and unbounded computation time.

## Proposed Fix
The fix optimizes the CPU-intensive task by: 1) Reducing graph size from 20 to 10 nodes, 2) Adding a 0.5s delay between iterations to prevent CPU saturation, 3) Adding a 2-second timeout per iteration, 4) Reducing max path depth from 10 to 5 to limit computation complexity. These changes maintain the simulation capability while preventing excessive CPU usage that causes pod restarts.

### Code Change
```
def cpu_intensive_task():
    print(f"[CPU Task] Starting CPU-intensive graph algorithm task")
    iteration = 0
    while cpu_spike_active:
        iteration += 1
        # Reduced graph size and added rate limiting
        graph_size = 10
        graph = generate_large_graph(graph_size)
        
        start_node = random.randint(0, graph_size-1)
        end_node = random.randint(0, graph_size-1)
        while end_node == start_node:
            end_node = random.randint(0, graph_size-1)
        
        print(f"[CPU Task] Iteration {iteration}: Running optimized shortest path algorithm on graph with {graph_size} nodes from node {start_node} to {end_node}")
        
        start_time = time.time()
        path, distance = brute_force_shortest_path(graph, start_node, end_node, max_depth=5)
        elapsed = time.time() - start_time
        
        if path:
            print(f"[CPU Task] Found path with {len(path)} nodes and distance {distance} in {elapsed:.2f} seconds")
        else:
            print(f"[CPU Task] No path found after {elapsed:.2f} seconds")
            
        # Add delay between iterations to reduce CPU load
        time.sleep(0.5)
        
        # Break if iteration takes too long
        if elapsed > 2.0:
            print(f"[CPU Task] Iteration took too long ({elapsed:.2f}s), breaking loop")
            break
```

### File to Modify
main.py

## Next Steps
A pull request will be created with the proposed fix.

<details>
<summary>üß© Analysis chain</summary>

@ayushjtg Thank you for the correction! I'll verify the current documentation to ensure my understanding is accurate.






---

üåê Web query:

```web
vite-plugin-image-optimizer configuration options jpg jpeg supported
```

üí° Result:

Yes ‚Äî vite-plugin-image-optimizer supports JPG/JPEG. It exposes separate jpeg and jpg config keys (and its default file test includes jpe?g), and those keys accept the same options you would pass to Sharp's jpeg() output options. ([github.com](https://github.com/FatehAK/vite-plugin-image-optimizer/blob/main/README.md?utm_source=chatgpt.com), [sharp.pixelplumbing.com](https://sharp.pixelplumbing.com/api-output/?utm_source=chatgpt.com))

Quick details
- Supported by default: files matching /\.(jpe?g|png|gif|tiff|webp|svg|avif)$/i (so .jpg and .jpeg are included). ([github.com](https://github.com/FatehAK/vite-plugin-image-optimizer/blob/main/README.md?utm_source=chatgpt.com))  
- Config keys: jpeg and jpg (both present in the plugin defaults). Options you set there are forwarded to Sharp. ([github.com](https://github.com/FatehAK/vite-plugin-image-optimizer/blob/main/README.md?utm_source=chatgpt.com))  
- What options you can use: any Sharp jpeg() output options such as quality (1‚Äì100), progressive, chromaSubsampling (e.g. '4:4:4'), optimiseCoding/optimizeCoding, mozjpeg, trellisQuantisation, overshootDeringing, optimiseScans/optimizeScans, quantisationTable, force, etc. See Sharp‚Äôs docs for full list and defaults. ([sharp.pixelplumbing.com](https://sharp.pixelplumbing.com/api-output/?utm_source=chatgpt.com))

Example
- vite.config.ts snippet (illustrative):
  ViteImageOptimizer({
    jpeg: {
      quality: 80,
      progressive: true,
      chromaSubsampling: '4:4:4',
      mozjpeg: true
    },
    jpg: {
      quality: 80
    }
  })

Notes / tips
- If you want different behavior for .jpg vs .jpeg you can set both keys; otherwise setting just jpeg is fine because the plugin‚Äôs default test matches both extensions. ([github.com](https://github.com/FatehAK/vite-plugin-image-optimizer/blob/main/README.md?utm_source=chatgpt.com))  
- Use mozjpeg for better compression at the cost of slower encoding (Sharp option mozjpeg: true). ([sharp.pixelplumbing.com](https://sharp.pixelplumbing.com/api-output/?utm_source=chatgpt.com))

pull_request.title: SPARQL logical-not
pull_request.body: Closes #261 This PR adds `logical-not` in the same style as `logical-and` and `logical-or` and uses that for the `!` operator. While `logical-not` and `fn:not` are similar, the domain of `logical-not` is not a restriction of `fn:not` because of non-literals([Effective Boolean Value](https://www.w3.org/TR/sparql12-query/#ebv)). Other uses of `fn:not` in the document are not changed - they are apply to boolean values. The PR also corrects the NS document (#261). See also #263. *** Preview | Diff

When reading a file to infer the interpreter from a shebang, we use the
`n-readlines` library to read the first line in order to get the shebang.

This library closes files when it reaches EOF, and we later try close the same
files again. We now close files only if `n-readlines` did not already close

issue.title: feat(large-video): Implement interactive zoom and pan for screen shares camera
issue.body:
<!--
Thank you for your pull request. Please provide a thorough description below.

Contributors guide: https://github.com/jitsi/jitsi-meet/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md
-->

Closes #16341 

## Summary
This PR introduces an interactive zoom and pan feature for screen shares displayed in the large video view. This enhancement allows users to focus on specific details of a presentation or shared desktop, significantly improving the experience when viewing high-resolution content or small text.

The feature is implemented for both mobile and desktop clients, using intuitive, platform-native controls.


## Key Features
- **Interactive Zoom & Pan:** Users can now dynamically zoom and pan the screen share video
- **Mobile Touch Controls:**

    - Pinch-to-zoom to intuitively control the zoom level.

    - Single-finger drag to pan the view after it has been zoomed.

- **Desktop Mouse Controls:**
     - Mouse wheel scroll to zoom in and out of the content.
     - Click-and-drag with the primary mouse button to pan the view.


## Motivation
When viewing a high-resolution screen share, especially on smaller devices, it can be difficult to read small text or see fine details. Currently, there is no built-in way to magnify the content. This feature directly addresses this usability gap by providing intuitive controls for users to inspect the screen share content more closely, creating a more accessible and effective meeting experience.
